I'm just curious, what are some of the decisions that have been made or big impacts

00:04:26.799 --> 00:04:34.079
to the business from data science? Yeah, so they vary from things that are more

00:04:34.079 --> 00:04:41.359
visible to you all, like what sizes should we sell on shelves? You know, like we've looked

00:04:41.359 --> 00:04:47.839
at things like how much difference does it make, pricing, how often we should promote,

00:04:48.399 --> 00:04:52.239
but there's also stuff we do on the back end a lot, like we've looked at.

00:04:54.799 --> 00:04:58.320
One of my favorite things to do is to get to actually run experiments in production. And

00:04:58.320 --> 00:05:02.640
our part of this is normally people asking like, okay, if we want to experiment with a different

00:05:02.640 --> 00:05:08.000
shape of bourbon barrel that will hold a bit more, how many do we need to test to make sure

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:13.679
that it doesn't have a negative yield impact? And that we're still getting the same amount,

00:05:13.679 --> 00:05:19.920
and then what impact might this have on color? How can we track all of those things on the back

00:05:19.920 --> 00:05:24.720
end? Cool. So did you end up changing the barrel size or shape?

00:05:25.359 --> 00:05:30.160
You know, that came to mind because I was recently asked about how many we need. I don't

00:05:30.160 --> 00:05:34.880
have the results of the experiment yet. I just figured out literally how many of the larger

00:05:34.880 --> 00:05:41.920
barrels we need to make in order to test it. That's cool. Seth, I see you just put a question

00:05:41.920 --> 00:05:47.600
into the chat if you want to ask live. Yeah, sure. As a recurring question,

00:05:47.600 --> 00:05:52.880
I'm very curious about, obviously we can't do the data science or analysis without the data. So

00:05:53.440 --> 00:05:59.359
I'm just curious where you guys generally get your data from and what processes you guys have

00:05:59.359 --> 00:06:03.359
for kind of ingesting it, prepping it so that you can kind of do the magic.

00:06:04.720 --> 00:06:10.799
Yeah. So there's a lot of different sources that we could talk through. So I'll talk about

00:06:11.359 --> 00:06:16.480
a few. So the pricing work that I've spent the most time with is honestly bought from Nielsen

00:06:16.480 --> 00:06:23.839
within the United States. Liquor has a three-tiered system. So we sell to a distributor

00:06:23.839 --> 00:06:29.839
who sells to a retailer who sells to a customer. So like I don't have any direct customer data,

00:06:29.839 --> 00:06:37.440
right? Like I have no idea who's buying what. So we get some aggregated data from Nielsen,

00:06:37.440 --> 00:06:42.000
which has bought it from those endpoint retailers in terms of how much they sold and at what price.

00:06:43.359 --> 00:06:47.839
And they get a lot of it from retailer scans and then sell that back to us.

00:06:49.040 --> 00:06:54.399
We have a data engineering team. So the process there looks roughly along the lines of Nielsen

00:06:54.399 --> 00:07:02.880
sends a data extract in some form of text file. The engineering team ingest it. They do a few

00:07:02.880 --> 00:07:08.880
joins for us ahead of time, expose it to us on a SQL server. And then we pull it down.

00:07:11.359 --> 00:07:15.359
We've got an R package that works on this. So we've got a script that essentially

00:07:17.920 --> 00:07:22.640
calls the functions we've written through pulling it from SQL, cleaning the data,

00:07:22.640 --> 00:07:27.359
transforming it, running the model. And then post-model, we also prep the data a bit

00:07:28.160 --> 00:07:32.720
before for things we want to do with the model of coefficients. So that we're not just saying,

00:07:32.720 --> 00:07:37.040
oh, your price LSD is this, but we're also breaking down how it matters. We also get

00:07:38.160 --> 00:07:43.519
a lot of data internally, more on the production side. And that's also transformed rapidly. 10

00:07:43.519 --> 00:07:49.119
years ago, our source of data would have been a clipboard that someone was writing on by hand.

00:07:49.679 --> 00:07:52.959
Actually, even five years ago, that would have been the case some places.

00:07:53.920 --> 00:07:59.279
So one of the things that, and that team is very heavily, they wind up doing a lot of data

00:07:59.279 --> 00:08:06.399
engineering, a lot of prepping for how do we even get and collect this data in the first place.

00:08:10.959 --> 00:08:18.480
We've had issues that we've tried to deal with. We want to know how big each barrel is. So we

00:08:19.279 --> 00:08:24.320
had a machine that rotates the barrel and in theory measures it with lasers, but occasionally

00:08:24.320 --> 00:08:29.119
this gets miscalibrated because I don't know, someone hits it with a forklift or just machines

00:08:29.119 --> 00:08:34.479
go out of calibration over time. And then we have to figure out like, what is the offset for this?

00:08:35.359 --> 00:08:41.760
What should it be? So there's that end is both. I mean, depending on your perspective,

00:08:41.760 --> 00:08:46.080
I think it's really fun in that we get to work with everything. Like what are the sensors in

00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:51.119
the warehouse? Where are they located? Temperature, humidity, like all sorts of

00:08:51.119 --> 00:08:56.000
fun, direct data collection, but also it means there's a lot of data engineering for that team.

00:08:56.880 --> 00:09:01.200
Thinking about even five years ago, people using clipboards and

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:07.200
tracking the data that way. I see Airfax had a question in the chat and said, curious to know,

00:09:07.200 --> 00:09:13.039
was there any particular project that helped to get buy-in from top management to expand

00:09:13.679 --> 00:09:23.280
to the data science route? Yeah. So I think the first one was actually the pricing. And the reason

00:09:23.280 --> 00:09:31.119
for this is the two types of projects that I think have gotten the most buy-in have so far

00:09:31.119 --> 00:09:36.400
been ones that directly replaced other things. And therefore it's easier to see what they're doing.

00:09:37.119 --> 00:09:42.960
And so they'd either replace an Excel process. It used to be the case that we might have an

00:09:42.960 --> 00:09:48.000
analyst spend a week figuring out a price elasticity for one model or for one market.

00:09:49.520 --> 00:09:57.200
And now once we have the process in place, we're using the same model in about 20 different

00:09:57.200 --> 00:10:02.880
countries and each country has multiple markets within it, et cetera. And so just the massive

00:10:02.880 --> 00:10:09.520
speed up of doing the same work with more accuracy, but also with more speed. And then when

00:10:09.520 --> 00:10:14.960
we've been able to replace consultants with data that it used to be the case, we would pay an

00:10:14.960 --> 00:10:23.039
outside analysis firm to do the analysis instead of internally setting that up. I think as I was

00:10:23.039 --> 00:10:28.479
talking through that, there's one third case that I forgot to mention that's possibly most relevant

00:10:28.479 --> 00:10:35.679
here. Our production team, when they were first introduced to Shiny apps, because they'd been

00:10:35.679 --> 00:10:42.880
trying to manage everything and sort of slowly going digital through going largely from patent

00:10:42.880 --> 00:10:50.080
paper to like Google Sheets occasionally. But it was very easy for one of our first data scientists

00:10:50.080 --> 00:10:56.799
in production to just spin up a Shiny app that would show them the things they needed because

00:10:56.799 --> 00:11:02.479
it could pull in data from multiple sources. It could do all the formatting within the app.

00:11:02.479 --> 00:11:10.719
It could give them a single place to go. So there was a pretty early transition, I think,

00:11:10.719 --> 00:11:15.919
within production to Shiny just proved out its value almost immediately in terms of, especially

00:11:15.919 --> 00:11:22.320
for the R&D team, the things they could look at. And I think one of the very first Shiny

00:11:22.320 --> 00:11:29.359
apps we deployed was just something where they wanted to run PCA analysis on some chemical

00:11:29.359 --> 00:11:33.919
results. And we're just like, OK, here's the thing where you can upload your CSV and then

00:11:33.919 --> 00:11:38.159
all of it will be run and you'll get all the charts you want right away. Right. And that

00:11:38.159 --> 00:11:43.599
just instantly saves hours of people's time. So that got a lot of buy in as well.

00:11:45.679 --> 00:11:55.760
That's great. Somebody had just asked me yesterday how to calculate ROI on switching over to data

00:11:55.760 --> 00:12:02.320
science tools, and they were just asking me if I had examples from different customers. But I feel

00:12:02.320 --> 00:12:09.440
like I never hear things in terms of dollar amounts of this is the exact ROI and that's so hard

00:12:09.440 --> 00:12:15.919
to calculate. And I was just curious if you had done that at all. Do you think of what the

00:12:15.919 --> 00:12:24.400
consultant's hourly cost was or what it costs in Excel? Yeah. So most formally, we have a project

00:12:24.400 --> 00:12:30.400
that tracks us through a Shiny app, of course, in production, but it tracks specifically process

00:12:30.400 --> 00:12:35.919
improvement. So that's that's one that that's easier to demonstrate, like if we run an experiment

00:12:35.919 --> 00:12:40.719
and it changes the process or it allows us to increase the yield coming out of our mills.

00:12:41.840 --> 00:12:46.559
I should say, I said Brownform is a liquor company. We also own the Cooperage that makes the

00:12:46.559 --> 00:12:51.520
barrels and we also buy the wood directly. So like that whole barrel making processes

00:12:52.479 --> 00:12:57.280
is within our scope. And when you're starting to look at those also warehouse conditions. So

00:12:58.239 --> 00:13:04.960
climate change has reduced bourbon yields, essentially like hotter conditions tend to mean

00:13:04.960 --> 00:13:09.359
we use less bourbon because more of it evaporates while it's sitting in the barrels.

00:13:09.919 --> 00:13:15.200
You know, so we've looked at things like how do we get back to that normal state? So when you

00:13:15.200 --> 00:13:21.760
can put it in yield terms, we don't have an overall ROI. We have,

00:13:24.239 --> 00:13:28.320
you know, like occasionally we get estimates of like what our work would have cost if it

00:13:28.320 --> 00:13:33.679
went through a consultant, but we've never actually like tried to add all of that up.

00:13:37.840 --> 00:13:42.880
Yeah, I don't often see it, but they're they're asking me for it. So I was like looking through

00:13:42.880 --> 00:13:49.520
like meetups and other recordings trying to see if people had mentioned that. I see Steve had

00:13:49.520 --> 00:13:54.640
asked on Slido, out of interest, what are the main computing platforms that you use?

00:13:57.440 --> 00:14:04.479
Yeah, so you're just looking for like where we actually do the math. We have

00:14:04.799 --> 00:14:12.640
we have our studio workbench on a fairly giant server, which is where we

00:14:14.880 --> 00:14:21.520
where we do our development. We are transitioning to also using a connect server for some of the

00:14:21.520 --> 00:14:26.080
stuff that's in production because it will allow us to automate and also it will allow us to

00:14:26.080 --> 00:14:32.640
separate production from dev. But maybe I should back up a second and just explain our general

00:14:33.440 --> 00:14:43.520
tool set. So we have our studio workbench where all of us can can log in. You know, it's set up

00:14:43.520 --> 00:14:48.640
on a Linux server with like a terabyte of RAM. We have nothing in the cloud. We do everything in

00:14:48.640 --> 00:14:54.719
house, so we need a fairly large server to accommodate all data scientists and any of the

00:14:54.719 --> 00:15:02.000
work we could perform. And generally that process will be we have a SQL database, a lot of stuff

00:15:02.400 --> 00:15:06.880
in Cloudera, although production has some of their own SQL servers that I think are Microsoft

00:15:06.880 --> 00:15:14.479
SQL servers still. And we'll wind up, you know, connecting through ODBC, pulling in our data,

00:15:15.200 --> 00:15:21.200
running the calculations in either R or Python, and then we will push them back to a database.

00:15:21.919 --> 00:15:27.760
And then from that, so we'll have our own section of the database that we run as an advanced

00:15:27.760 --> 00:15:34.239
analytics team. And then we will build the front end app in either Shiny or Tableau off of that

00:15:34.239 --> 00:15:44.159
transformed data. I see Arifath, you just asked another question that yeah, you mentioned I should

00:15:44.159 --> 00:15:51.039
read live. So if possible, could you please shed some more light on the kind of post model work

00:15:51.039 --> 00:16:00.159
that you perform? Sure. So, you know, for our price elasticities, like we build a model of

00:16:01.119 --> 00:16:06.320
the entire market. So it's not just price, it's also distribution, how many stores is it in,

00:16:06.320 --> 00:16:12.640
how is the category performs in like whiskey doing, how is the overall spirits market doing,

00:16:12.640 --> 00:16:20.320
etc. And, you know, one of the things we do is we go back through the past year and we say,

00:16:21.840 --> 00:16:29.919
okay, if we compare the last 13 weeks of sales to the same 13 week period a year ago,

00:16:30.559 --> 00:16:36.239
and we apply our price elasticity to the actual pricing difference that we observed historically,

00:16:36.239 --> 00:16:42.000
what's the impact in actual case volume. So we're, we're presenting our users with something where

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:47.840
they can say, oh, if I'm looking at like, this most recent week, you know, rolled up to account

00:16:47.840 --> 00:16:52.320
for some noise. But if I'm looking at what's happening now, not just what was the price

00:16:52.320 --> 00:16:56.320
elasticity, but how did that actually impact me based on what was happening in prices at the

00:16:56.320 --> 00:17:04.800
market. And we've also, you know, rolled out something where, you know, using shiny users

00:17:04.800 --> 00:17:10.160
can upload like, this is my pricing plan for next year, what would your model predict is going to

00:17:10.160 --> 00:17:18.079
happen. Right. So the idea is that we're really as much as possible, giving them that part of that

00:17:18.079 --> 00:17:23.760
is because users would try to do these with the, do these things with the price elasticity

00:17:23.760 --> 00:17:29.040
coefficients on their own. And not only does that take a lot more time if a bunch of different

00:17:29.040 --> 00:17:33.680
people are, you know, repeatedly doing the same math and different accessories, but it also was

00:17:33.680 --> 00:17:38.719
pretty air prone. And people did not always understand the model. There are good reasons

00:17:38.719 --> 00:17:44.719
to, you know, use the entire model as a whole and not just look at like, what would happen if I

00:17:44.719 --> 00:17:52.160
changed the price, but actually enter a plan for, you know, price, competitors, price, whiskey segments, etc.

