00:22:15.040 --> 00:22:20.479
nice if the rest of the organization would do things in more of the data science way, of course,

00:22:20.479 --> 00:22:25.280
but like we have enough people who want our help that I'm not going to like push data science

00:22:25.280 --> 00:22:31.599
on people who don't want our help yet. So we've been pretty much able to just work with the

00:22:31.599 --> 00:22:40.479
problems that people have. We've also, so I guess the one exception to that perhaps is we've been

00:22:40.479 --> 00:22:47.680
working on adoption. So, you know, like within pricing, there's, there's a lot of support from

00:22:48.719 --> 00:22:52.160
corporate and for some of the high level folks, but then you get into the question of, well,

00:22:52.160 --> 00:22:58.560
what if we're reaching out to salespeople on the ground and to some of the smaller countries,

00:22:58.560 --> 00:23:04.719
smaller markets doing some trainings there? And I mean, that's largely like, again, our,

00:23:04.719 --> 00:23:09.680
our partners who actually do pricing, reaching out to those other folks, but we have been trying

00:23:09.680 --> 00:23:15.040
to focus a lot of our tools on adoption. So that comes both in the occasional training meeting,

00:23:15.040 --> 00:23:23.280
but also documentation, usability of tools. Most of our revisions are focused not now on adding

00:23:23.280 --> 00:23:28.319
new features, but on making existing features clearer, making it easier for end users to work

00:23:28.319 --> 00:23:36.319
with. Nate, I see there's two questions that are kind of similar around Shiny and Tableau.

00:23:37.040 --> 00:23:42.239
So one said, you've mentioned Shiny and Tableau for your team. What goes into deciding when to

00:23:42.239 --> 00:23:50.800
use which? And then I see that Ian also added, does it have to do with end user or functionality,

00:23:50.800 --> 00:24:00.079
for example? Yeah. So it has to do with, with a lot of push things. So, I mean, one of the first

00:24:00.079 --> 00:24:05.280
criteria, of course, is if it's not something you can do in Tableau, then we're going to use Shiny

00:24:05.280 --> 00:24:12.959
for it. And then there's no decision. Another one that, that sort of shortcuts it is we think about

00:24:12.959 --> 00:24:19.839
who not necessarily at the end user is, but the end maintainer. And so the reason the end user

00:24:19.839 --> 00:24:27.359
matters less to us is we have a reasonably consistent sort of design across Shiny and

00:24:27.359 --> 00:24:31.760
Tableau. Like folks generally know, we're going to have some filters on the left. We're going to

00:24:31.760 --> 00:24:36.400
have a nice header telling you what it does. It's going to incorporate a little bit of our branding,

00:24:36.400 --> 00:24:41.839
and then we're going to have some graphs in the main panel that react to the filters on the side.

00:24:42.640 --> 00:24:48.319
So we've never really had trouble with users being confused anymore by Shiny or Tableau.

00:24:49.839 --> 00:24:55.680
And then we have a corporate center that links dashboards. And of course, you can also just send

00:24:55.680 --> 00:25:01.520
people links directly. So it hasn't really been a problem for end users. Where it does matter

00:25:01.680 --> 00:25:06.800
sometimes we as a team are responsible for initially building dashboards that we want

00:25:06.800 --> 00:25:11.920
other folks in the business to maintain. And if we want someone else to maintain it,

00:25:11.920 --> 00:25:18.959
then we're a lot more likely to use Tableau. Of our team of 14 data scientists, we probably

00:25:18.959 --> 00:25:25.839
have five that are pretty good at building Shiny apps and can build and maintain Shiny apps.

00:25:25.839 --> 00:25:31.760
But that's it for the entire organization. Whereas we probably have about 100 folks who

00:25:31.760 --> 00:25:37.839
can at least build basic Tableau apps. Now, although some are much more advanced and can

00:25:37.839 --> 00:25:45.280
build much more complex things, but just not the user of the dashboard, but the user in terms of

00:25:46.560 --> 00:25:51.119
the people maintaining dashboards, there's a much bigger base for Tableau. And so that

00:25:51.119 --> 00:26:04.239
can come into consideration. The functionality has probably been the biggest thing. So using

00:26:04.239 --> 00:26:11.760
Shiny, you know, you get version control, you get the ability to be a lot more flexible with

00:26:11.760 --> 00:26:16.079
your data and your setup. You get the fact that you can really go end to end within a Shiny app.

00:26:16.079 --> 00:26:23.119
So in many cases, it's a lot faster. I can often, if it's, you know, like if it's a small

00:26:23.119 --> 00:26:30.079
enough data transformation, you know, I can just work within R the whole time, quickly build a

00:26:30.079 --> 00:26:34.239
Shiny app, look at my results right away. I don't have to wait for this step of even like,

00:26:35.040 --> 00:26:40.800
oh, I'm going to output this even to a CSV or to a database and then run Tableau on top of it.

00:26:41.599 --> 00:26:51.199
So there's, I suppose it's a bit less of a consideration, but still, I think a relevant

00:26:51.199 --> 00:26:56.479
consideration of like, what does the person building the dashboard want to use? And what

00:26:56.479 --> 00:27:03.520
are they fastest at? You know, Tableau can make some data transformations much more difficult

00:27:03.520 --> 00:27:07.439
than if you're working in R or Python, like it is set up as a visualization tool.

00:27:07.439 --> 00:27:13.040
And I think Tableau is in fact an excellent visualization tool. The problems I observe

00:27:13.040 --> 00:27:18.400
in organizations are when they try to push tools too far outside of what they're designed for.

00:27:21.439 --> 00:27:26.400
And so like our prominent, you know, our most prominent Shiny apps where we just couldn't do

00:27:26.400 --> 00:27:31.280
it in Tableau is our forecasting work, where we want users to be able to interact with the

00:27:31.280 --> 00:27:36.239
forecast and like set some of the predictions. And so that's where Tableau comes in.

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:43.839
And then we're going to run the forecast in the background. And then while some of our pricing

00:27:43.839 --> 00:27:48.800
stuff is, is in Tableau, you know, some of it where like, if we want users to be able to upload

00:27:48.800 --> 00:27:53.599
any sort of data and then interact with models and so forth, that's all stuff that's going to

00:27:53.599 --> 00:28:00.880
wind up being in Shiny. We just have a lot of additional flexibility that way. Would you be

00:28:00.880 --> 00:28:07.680
able to, just for my understanding, to be able to give an example of what's something that would

00:28:07.680 --> 00:28:12.479
need to be a Shiny app because of the model or what's like an exact example versus something

00:28:12.479 --> 00:28:21.439
that would be in Tableau? The two biggest ones I've seen are needing users to upload data.

00:28:22.319 --> 00:28:26.560
You know, like we tried something with some financial gaming in Tableau where people had

00:28:26.560 --> 00:28:31.520
to like enter by hand into input boxes, just like everything they wanted. And it just didn't get used

00:28:31.520 --> 00:28:36.079
because it's a pain to enter data that way. You know, like, whereas we've been able to give them

00:28:37.439 --> 00:28:41.439
in a Shiny app, like here, you can download last year's data as a default,

00:28:41.439 --> 00:28:46.959
change the things you want to change, upload it and see what our model says. The other one is,

00:28:46.959 --> 00:28:53.359
is connecting directly to outside APIs. Tableau probably has some of this, but our institutional

00:28:53.359 --> 00:28:59.199
Tableau, we can't add Tableau extensions. So we really are just dealing with like base Tableau.

00:28:59.199 --> 00:29:03.520
So like we wanted to pull Google Trends into a dashboard, and this is easy enough in R.

00:29:03.520 --> 00:29:07.839
There's a package for it. We pull it in, we make some nice graphs, and that's something we just

00:29:07.839 --> 00:29:15.680
couldn't do in Tableau. Thank you. Yeah, I think it's helpful to just understand, like, because

00:29:15.680 --> 00:29:20.319
both are great tools, but understanding when you would use one versus when you use the other

00:29:20.880 --> 00:29:27.119
and being able to communicate that out to the team too. Yeah, and I mean, the more calculations

00:29:27.119 --> 00:29:32.800
in general you try to put into Tableau, the harder it gets to use and maintain the workbook.

00:29:32.800 --> 00:29:36.880
You know, like when people have to use, especially other people's Tableau workbooks,

00:29:37.599 --> 00:29:41.920
going back through it and like unlayering and figuring out the dependencies and so forth

00:29:42.640 --> 00:29:46.560
of, you know, which calculation relies on which other three calculations,

00:29:46.800 --> 00:29:53.520
and what is the actual math here becomes fairly tricky. Like it's not the best tool

00:29:53.520 --> 00:29:57.040
for all of your data manipulations, even though it can do some of them.

00:29:59.359 --> 00:30:04.079
Thank you. Laura, I see you asked a great question about how they're using

00:30:04.079 --> 00:30:07.119
data science today. Would you want to ask that one live?

00:30:08.079 --> 00:30:15.280
Yeah. Hi, Nate. I find this talk super interesting. I actually used to work for

00:30:16.560 --> 00:30:20.719
Irish distillers. So I was working on all the Irish whiskeys back in Ireland

00:30:21.439 --> 00:30:25.520
in the marketing area. And I kind of noticed that they were really trying to make a big effort to

00:30:25.520 --> 00:30:31.920
bring in AI and ML, particularly around our packaging. And I was just wondering,

00:30:32.880 --> 00:30:37.680
does either your teams do anything in the marketing and advertising space in relation to

00:30:38.239 --> 00:30:42.560
data science and analytics? Yeah, so hopefully I won't get

00:30:42.560 --> 00:30:50.560
myself in too much trouble with my answer here. So I have talked to marketing and analytics.

00:30:50.560 --> 00:30:54.959
And the truth is usually when they come to me with a question of like, can you tell us what

00:30:54.959 --> 00:31:00.000
was the effect of this marketing campaign? My answer is no, I can't. Because every time I've

00:31:00.000 --> 00:31:04.400
tried, I don't just say no up front. I'm like, OK, what data do we have? Let's take a look,

00:31:04.400 --> 00:31:12.560
et cetera. But my answer does wind up being no, there's not enough. The short-term effects are

00:31:12.560 --> 00:31:16.800
usually too small to capture. The long-term effects, well, there's just too much going on

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:24.479
with the long-term. But I also think it's interesting that you brought up where they

00:31:24.479 --> 00:31:30.400
want to go with AI and machine learning, because that's not at all really where I'm pushing them.

00:31:30.400 --> 00:31:36.319
I'm pushing them to run experiments. I think they should do A-B testing. I do not think

00:31:37.760 --> 00:31:46.400
adding AI or ML is going to fundamentally solve the problems we have of not having good data,

00:31:47.520 --> 00:31:53.680
having too many things going on at once. Yes, you're going to get some sort of pattern,

00:31:54.959 --> 00:32:01.359
but fundamentally, I think in order to actually evaluate marketing,

00:32:02.160 --> 00:32:07.680
you need to collect better data, and you need to actually be intentional about causal inference.

00:32:07.680 --> 00:32:14.160
And the easiest way to do this is going to be some sort of A-B testing. I'll actually say more

00:32:14.160 --> 00:32:23.119
broadly, while AI and machine learning gets a lot of hype, I know the common joke that

00:32:23.119 --> 00:32:28.880
80% of the time, the business just needs a SQL query with a group by, but the other 20% of the

00:32:28.880 --> 00:32:31.920
time, they need something more advanced. I think what they need is causal inference.

00:32:33.040 --> 00:32:39.359
Most of the time, the business is not, and this does vary, but at least in my line of work,

00:32:39.359 --> 00:32:44.959
most of the time, the business, for me, wants to know, did my campaign cause something to happen?

00:32:44.959 --> 00:32:50.719
Did the price change cause something to happen? There are businesses I know where the prediction

00:32:51.119 --> 00:32:58.719
is fine. Is this part going to wear out in so many years? There's some stuff, and obviously,

00:32:58.719 --> 00:33:06.479
if you're dealing with image data or text and so forth, AI and machine learning is a huge revelation

00:33:06.479 --> 00:33:14.880
there. But for a lot of your day-to-day business questions, you need data to be better organized,

00:33:14.880 --> 00:33:19.599
you need research design, and you need some understanding of causal inference.

00:33:21.359 --> 00:33:29.520
That's a great question, Laura. I had a follow-up on that, too. If that is what you need,

00:33:29.520 --> 00:33:36.079
but you don't have that today, how do you communicate that to the team or teach them

00:33:36.079 --> 00:33:42.239
maybe what data they should have? Yeah. We've been working on that,

00:33:42.239 --> 00:33:51.199
actually, with marketing and analytics, and a lot of this is internal education. We'll see

00:33:51.760 --> 00:33:58.719
how well it works. We're moving a little at a time. Our basic pitch has been to, first of all,

00:33:58.719 --> 00:34:03.760
just explain what A-B testing is for folks who aren't familiar. I think it tends to be a good

00:34:03.760 --> 00:34:11.280
entryway to understanding research design because as research designs go, it's on the simpler end.

00:34:11.280 --> 00:34:14.719
We're going to have two groups. We're going to compare them. You're going to need us to

00:34:14.719 --> 00:34:20.560
help you set up the groups. That I also will say you need to stress because there have been

00:34:20.560 --> 00:34:26.959
occasions in the past where folks did think they were doing some sort of test, and what they did

00:34:26.959 --> 00:34:31.760
was they said, we're going to run a huge media campaign in the markets that are performing best

00:34:31.760 --> 00:34:37.520
right now and not in the other ones. They were doing this for strategic reasons, and it makes

00:34:37.520 --> 00:34:43.600
sense perhaps as a strategy, but it also completely invalidates any sort of test if

00:34:44.159 --> 00:34:51.360
you're shifting your funding based on which markets are performing well and not as a way

00:34:51.360 --> 00:34:58.639
to test the actual effect of expenditures. Then we've also been trying to get them to just start

00:34:58.639 --> 00:35:07.120
small and on things that are less threatening. Any sort of test that could result in funding

00:35:07.120 --> 00:35:12.719
being cut, there's always going to be pushback on that, right? Right now, they're getting the

00:35:12.719 --> 00:35:18.639
funding. They're doing the marketing. Things are going well. Why do a test when that can pretty

00:35:18.639 --> 00:35:24.159
much only result in bad news for them? We're trying to introduce this as a way to just at

00:35:24.159 --> 00:35:28.959
first test two different creatives against each other. You're still going to run something,

00:35:28.959 --> 00:35:35.280
but why don't we run the more effective of the two creative materials? The hope is that that's

00:35:35.280 --> 00:35:41.520
going to get some research design involved, but this is stuff we're working on now, so

00:35:42.479 --> 00:35:47.199
you'll have to ask me in a year or two if this actually worked at all or if it just ran into a

00:35:47.199 --> 00:35:55.360
dead end. Thanks, Nate. That's really helpful. Frank, I see you just put a question in the chat

00:35:55.360 --> 00:36:06.719
if you want to ask that one live. I do. Thanks, Rachel. Nate, I'm curious. Is all the work that

00:36:06.719 --> 00:36:14.080
your teams do one, what I said, one problem to one solution, meaning you get with your

00:36:14.080 --> 00:36:18.639
stakeholders or your users and say, hey, what's the problem you need to solve? Okay, great.

00:36:18.639 --> 00:36:23.120
Understand the problem. Let's build a solution, right? Maybe you maintain that. Maybe it's a

00:36:23.120 --> 00:36:28.639
one-time analysis. Is there anything that you've worked on and your teams have worked on that

00:36:29.280 --> 00:36:33.919
you've been able to say, oh, there's a problem here, here, and here? They have very similar

00:36:33.919 --> 00:36:39.840
characteristics. Can we build something that can serve all three of those groups?

00:36:42.639 --> 00:36:48.159
And right then you can scale a little bit better, but a lot of the problems that I see coming to me

00:36:48.159 --> 00:36:52.959
and my team and a lot of other data science teams are, hey, here's my problem, and then we do a lot

00:36:52.959 --> 00:36:56.560
of work and we solve that problem, and then we have this thing to support and maintain,

00:36:56.560 --> 00:37:00.479
and then we do that a hundred times and we're like, oh my gosh, we're maintaining everything.

00:37:02.479 --> 00:37:08.239
So I'm wondering if anything pops to mind. Yeah. So one, certainly we have the same thing

00:37:08.239 --> 00:37:13.520
with stakeholders where they have one problem in mind that they want us to solve. I do think

00:37:15.040 --> 00:37:21.919
our price elasticity work does fall into this category. So one of the things is we initially

00:37:21.919 --> 00:37:25.439
insisted on, well, we're going to need a bunch of data because if we're going to understand the

00:37:25.439 --> 00:37:29.840
effect of price, we need to simultaneously understand the effect of other things that

00:37:29.840 --> 00:37:36.080
are going on. So as it turns out in our quest to just model price elasticities, we also have a way

00:37:36.080 --> 00:37:40.479
to think about competitive sets, like who's actually competing with you on price. We have a

00:37:40.479 --> 00:37:47.760
way to think about distribution. We have a way to think about, we've also used it for bottle size

00:37:47.760 --> 00:37:59.360
changes. And then one other issue that we have that I'm trying to solve with modifications

00:37:59.360 --> 00:38:04.719
of the model, and this may sound weird, although all of you are in the industry, but like defining

00:38:04.719 --> 00:38:10.959
what a product is, is a non-trivial task. That's why I said it would sound weird. Like you think,

00:38:10.959 --> 00:38:16.879
oh, it's 750 milliliters of Jack Daniels. But if we change the design, is it the same?

00:38:17.120 --> 00:38:21.199
If we change the color just a little, is it the same or different? If we pair it with a shot glass,

00:38:21.199 --> 00:38:26.159
is it the same or different? Well, clearly it's different. And clearly it also is going to take

00:38:26.159 --> 00:38:33.760
away sales. So what do we do when it comes to the gift packaging essentially that we model

00:38:33.760 --> 00:38:38.800
all of the time? Is that a separate problem or can we combine it in with our price elasticity models?

00:38:39.439 --> 00:38:46.159
So what we have tried to do, I think, in the spirit of this is we really are trying to get

00:38:46.159 --> 00:38:51.919
to a place where we have a model of the market and it answers a bunch of questions because it's

00:38:51.919 --> 00:38:58.719
taking a fairly holistic view of the market. So it can help us answer out-of-stock questions. It

00:38:58.719 --> 00:39:04.080
can help us answer questions about gift, about promotions, about all of this. And it's also

00:39:05.120 --> 00:39:14.479
one model. So from like zero to a hundred percent, where do you think you are from where you want to

00:39:14.479 --> 00:39:26.159
be? I'll go with 60 maybe. We actually have, I mean, most of this stuff works. We still have a

00:39:26.159 --> 00:39:32.080
bit of an issue there, but we are able to use it to look at counterfactual situations, look at

00:39:32.080 --> 00:39:39.439
actual situations. We have gotten fairly good adoption of let's look at the market this way.

00:39:40.239 --> 00:39:42.719
Right on. Cool. Thank you.

00:39:45.280 --> 00:39:52.399
Thanks, Nate. Arafat asked a question earlier that was how do you do different work? So for

00:39:52.399 --> 00:39:57.760
example, data process, collection, model building, API development in your team.

00:39:58.560 --> 00:40:03.840
Do you have dedicated people for certain tasks or is it more like everyone is doing some of

00:40:03.840 --> 00:40:10.959
everything? Yeah. So this is a great question because I know it's a very ongoing debate in

00:40:10.959 --> 00:40:18.159
like how to organize data science teams and if we should have specialists. And the answer within

00:40:18.159 --> 00:40:26.479
our team is some of both. We do want people to be able to go fairly end-to-end on data science

00:40:26.479 --> 00:40:34.560
products and also to get a chance to do different things. Like people stuck only

00:40:34.560 --> 00:40:38.959
developing front-end dashboards are people who are going to get tired of developing front-end

00:40:38.959 --> 00:40:44.479
dashboards eventually almost no matter how much they like it. So we do want people to get to

00:40:44.479 --> 00:40:51.120
rotate. Probably our biggest restriction is like we've got three people on our team who can

00:40:51.120 --> 00:40:57.439
actually push stuff to the database. So like in terms of administration, we do have some stuff

00:40:57.439 --> 00:41:04.000
there. We do have some folks who are a bit more on the data engineering side. And while we

00:41:04.000 --> 00:41:11.199
encourage people to develop skills across all things, certainly like not everyone is equally

00:41:11.199 --> 00:41:20.719
proficient across R, Python, Tableau, and SQL. And so what you have will depend on what people's

00:41:20.719 --> 00:41:28.959
skills are and what they're trying to develop. But even across the tech, I mean it looks like

00:41:28.959 --> 00:41:34.080
you're also talking about you know process and collection, model building, experimentation,

00:41:34.080 --> 00:41:43.600
maintenance, etc. Yet for the most part, we tend to divide that by business area rather

00:41:43.600 --> 00:41:49.439
than by tech within. So like someone in production will actually be out at the production site

00:41:49.439 --> 00:41:53.679
thinking about the sensors and how they get that into the database. And then they're also

00:41:53.679 --> 00:41:58.399
going to build the model based on the temperature data collected from that sensors. And that doesn't

00:41:58.399 --> 00:42:02.800
mean like you know within the hub we have some people who specialize more in modeling and they're

00:42:02.800 --> 00:42:07.600
going to talk to those people about like what's an appropriate statistical model here. But yeah

00:42:07.600 --> 00:42:12.239
they're going to code it. They're going to own it. They're going to be responsible for usually

00:42:12.239 --> 00:42:21.360
maintaining what they build. Awesome, thank you. I love thinking about how like your data science

00:42:21.360 --> 00:42:29.360
team is actually like right there where they're making the whiskey too. So there's a few other

00:42:29.360 --> 00:42:33.919
anonymous questions too that came in earlier. And one was when you were talking a bit about

00:42:34.719 --> 00:42:42.320
marketing experiments, someone said could you please share any actual examples of the experiments

00:42:42.320 --> 00:42:47.840
run? I would love to because I would love to get marketing to run an actual experiment.

00:42:49.840 --> 00:42:56.239
So no this is still something we're trying to get them. So I think one of the issues here is

00:42:57.040 --> 00:43:03.520
you know I've said hey I've worked through this data. I've built out the model and you know

00:43:03.520 --> 00:43:10.080
when I do all reasonable things that you can do to the data I just don't see this effect. I can't

00:43:10.080 --> 00:43:18.879
detect it. Doesn't mean it's not there per se but so while I can say that internally a consultant

00:43:18.879 --> 00:43:22.800
does not have to say that. They will tell you they can in fact see the effect of your marketing

00:43:22.800 --> 00:43:31.040
campaign. I had a lengthy back and forth with with the consultant asking in their about

00:43:31.040 --> 00:43:36.800
their methodology and you know essentially they're overfitting the data. You know like

00:43:36.800 --> 00:43:44.320
they're getting there by well yeah by pretty blatantly overfitting the data. But then you

00:43:44.320 --> 00:43:48.879
know we're in a situation where the consultant is giving a report that says hey what you're doing

00:43:48.879 --> 00:43:53.280
works and I'm giving a report that says hey I don't know you need better research design.

00:43:54.000 --> 00:44:00.479
